-I am a tank<br>
-I have a pet that is even more dependant on seeing backside to do damage than a mage pet.<br>
<br>
There are two sides to this:<br>
<br>
1) A good tank, if everything is going well, will position the mob and keep everyone and everything else behind the mob.  However, perfect conditions do not always exist and shtuff happens.  As a tank, I will position the mob to the best of my ability with pets, rogues, rangers, etc behind it.<br>
<br>
2) ANY pet class that places their pet too high on the importance list needs to reevaluate their priorities.  Group dynamics and using each class to its fullest IS the responsibility of the GROUP, but there is a point past which I assume you will take care of your own class issues....  I expect NO ONE else to accomodate my pet, although I might ask someone to try something a tad different if I feel it won't be too much of a chore for them.  All pet classes know pathing blows... there are times the tank has much more to worry about than the life of a pet, and pet owners are usually more equipped to handle said issues.<br>
<br>
Example: party is rocking and mobs are dying left and right...  I ask that the Warrior tanking moves ever so slightly to the right allowing my pet to get behind... warrior agrees as my pet can add some surprising damage despite its un-uberness.<br>
<br>
Example2: Party was trained... I am tanking and the slow landed by the chanter gets him a nice beating.... then two more mobs join in.  I don't care about the dang pet.. in fact, If I can get the pet killed and save the chanter/cleric/ (insert player class here) I am going to... taunting and getting aggro in a hurry is primary... Its a minor consideration where that pet is &quot;dumbpathing&quot; to and dying to rage because its owner can't reel it in.<br>
<br>
In short,  the spirit of the original post was fine...  however, the attitude I got when I read it (and re-read it) was closer to &quot;YOU need to make my pets do their extra 5DPS&quot;.  I know that wasn't the spirit of that post, but I couldn't help but getting that from it.<br>
<br>
I agree with the statement tanks should do their best to try to optimize such things...<br>
<br>
I disagree with the idea that it is ALL the tanks job (or even that its mostly their job).  The pet owner should mention tips how to use their talents better... the tank should do their best to help out, but the pet's usefulness rests mostly in the hands of the pet owner.  Anything else on the part of the pet owner is just laziness.<br>
<br>
If I can feign pull, MT (and add-tank at the same time), cycle short duration group buffs/taps, nuke, debuff, and control my pet, (Hybrids rarely get to med in a group) then a mage can handle nuke, debuff, med, and their pet.<br>
<br>
