<br>
Actually, at least in my experience, for a raid this isn't true.  What happens is the MT positions the mob in the place and facing the direction that is the best for the raid, such as head first into a corner, or walking it up and down a hall, or facing it in the direction where its knock back won't send everyone careening through the air to their deaths, or where the Clerics can position themselves safely and still perform the CH cycle or whatever.<br>
<br>
The pets and rogues accommodate the direction the mob needs to face due the situation, not their preference.  The needs of the raid out weigh the desires of the pet users and Rogues.  And this is as it should be.  This is of course for a raid.<br>
<br>
Now, does a group MT have some leeway and control in which way a mob faces?  Yes.  Does he necessarily have complete control of where the mob is?  No, not necessarily.  Many times circumstances or other player actions will cause a mob to be in a less than ideal position.  Then the MT can just do the best he can.  Saying its completely under his control is wrong.  <p>The Man in Black: We are men of action, lies do not become us. <br>
